Title: M-eyeBall: Model EyeBall for Medical Students
Description:
Use the DIY M-eyeBall to practice dexterity and orientation for slit lamp and indirect ophthalmoscopy. This can be made with inexpensive household items and is intended for medical students applying into ophthalmology. M-eyeBall idea, design, and video created by Jacob Abou-Hanna, student at University of Michigan Medical School.

Tips: 
-Use a nail with nail-head diameter of 5-8mm (to simulate a dilated pupil)
-Adjust hanger dimensions if needed, depending on slit lamp model
-Practice caution when using the blade!

Title: Diabetic Retinopathy Research Update
Description: Thomas W. Gardner, M.D., M.S., studies the effects of diabetes on the retina. His research focuses on the development of new treatments to help slow the progression of diabetic retinopathy.

Title: Please tell us about your research in gene and stem cell therapy.
Description: Robin Ali, BSc, PhD, FMedSci, internationally known for his research in gene and cell-based therapy for the treatment of retinal degeneration, has joined the U-M Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences as a Visiting Professor. Dr. Ali, professor of human molecular genetics, directs the Department of Genetics at University College London's Institute of Ophthalmology and Moorfields Eye Hospital. Dr. Ali will collaborate with faculty at the Kellogg Eye Center to advance research toward treatments for inherited retinal disease.

Title: Medicine Needs Victors: Roger Pontz and The Bionic Eye Team
Description:
University of Michigan's Victors for Michigan campaign 

Diagnosed with retinitis pigmentosa as a teenager, Pontz has been almost completely blind for years. Now, thanks to a high-tech procedure that involved the surgical implantation of a "bionic eye," he's regained enough of his eyesight to catch small glimpses of his wife, grandson and cat.

Title: The Eyes Have It: a mobile app for iPhones and iPads
Description:
The Eyes Have It (TEHI) app is designed to teach medical and optometric students, and to assist physicians, optometrists, ophthalmic technicians, nurses and other health care providers in managing eye care problems. 

The text is written by respected University of Michigan ophthalmologist Jonathan D. Trobe, M.D.  Images, narrated animations, and videos illustrate the clinical and teaching points.  

With 134 eye conditions, 410 images, more than 40 narrated animations and videos, 6 screening exams and an eye anatomy review section, this pocket resource can be your go-to source for eye information!

For more information visit: 
http://www.kellogg.umich.edu/theeyeshaveit/app.html

Description: Meet Linda Schulte, the 1st recipient of the Argus II Retinal Prosthesis System at Kellogg.  What does she hope the retinal implant will allow her to do? To see?  Listen in...

Title: Surgeons implant 1st bionic eye since FDA approval
Description: Retina surgeons at the University of Michigan Kellogg Eye Center have performed the first — and second — surgeries in the U.S. to implant an artificial retina, or "bionic eye," since the FDA approved the device last year. Thiran Jayasundera, M.D., and David N. Zacks, M.D., Ph.D., performed the surgeries for patients with end-stage retinitis pigmentosa (RP), a degenerative and blinding eye disease.

Title: Ribbon cutting ceremony at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
Bill and Dee Brehm and Dr. Paul Lichter do the ribbon cutting honors.  A choir of U-M students perform Bill Brehm's composition, "Our Michigan."

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: James O. Woolliscroft, M.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
A synergy will be created when diabetes and vision researchers are able to work together, said Dr. James Woolliscroft, dean of the Medical School. "I am excited about the miracles to come that will happen within these walls," he said. "Medicine at Michigan is stronger than ever."

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Gail R. Wilensky, Ph.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
Keynote speaker Gail Wilensky, John M. Olin Senior Fellow at Project Hope, said forces that made creation of the building possible — partnership and philanthropy — are typical only in the United States. "Private philanthropy is a uniquely American strategy that is needed now more than ever," she said. "It is the hope that this type of collective research will dominate research in the future."

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Roy Pedersen, A.I.A., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
Architecture firm TSA of Massachusetts created a building modern in design with features intended to evoke a warm and welcoming environment. "We look forward to reading about the wonderful things that come out of this building," said architect Roy Pedersen.

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Paul A. Sieving, M.D., Ph.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description: Dr. Paul Sieving, director of the National Eye Institute and a former U-M ophthalmology professor, said, "This dedication marks the start of new research in diabetes and eye care." He added that the proximity of researchers in both areas offers "a major new opportunity for both to prosper."

Title: Douglas L. Strong, M.B.A., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
The new addition fills a need to expand research programs with state-of-the-art clinics, said Douglas Strong, director and CEO of the U-M Hospitals and Health Centers. "We are not only bigger but much, much better," he said.

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Ora Hirsch Pescovitz, M.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
Dr. Ora Hirsch Pescovitz, executive vice president for medical affairs and chief executive officer of UMHS, said the unique vision of the Brehms and supporters of the eye center has opened "an important chapter in innovation and groundbreaking science." "We are looking to find a cure for diabetes and the broad spectrum of eye diseases that plague humanity. We will find a cure for diabetes."

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Paul R. Lichter, M.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
"The science in the new building, in collaboration with the Brehm Center for Diabetes Research, will be profound, " said Paul R. Lichter, Director of the W.K. Kellogg Eye Center and Chair of the Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences.  "We look forward to what develops from this new facility."

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Mary Sue Coleman, Ph.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
President Mary Sue Coleman recalled the history of the W.K. Kellogg Foundation and the generosity of its founder, Will Kellogg, who suffered from glaucoma and supported efforts to improve vision care and provide services to the blind. "'I would give all my money,' he said, 'just to see the sun and green grass again,'" Coleman said.  "It is that simple desire to see the world that drives our students, our faculty and staff, and the generous donors who support the constant quest for answers at the Kellogg Eye Center."

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Peter Arvan, M.D., Ph.D., speaks at the dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
"New shoots are popping up out of the ground. This new shoot creates both clinical and research opportunities we've never had before," said Dr. Peter Arvan, Brehm Professor of Type 1 Diabetes Research, chief of the Division of Metabolism, Endocrinology & Diabetes, and director of the Comprehensive Diabetes Center.

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu

Title: Dedication of the Brehm Tower at the Kellogg Eye Center
Description:
On April 23, 2010, the U-M Health System formally dedicated the new Brehm Tower at the W.K. Kellogg Eye Center Complex with a "Dedicated to Discovery" ceremony.  Dr. Paul Lichter, chair of the Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences and director of the Kellogg Eye Center, welcomed an estimated 700 friends, faculty and staff who came to celebrate a new facility designed to enhance UMHS' capacity for eye care research and education and to unite diabetes researchers as they accelerate the search for a cure and prevention of diabetes.

Learn more at: http://www.kellogg.umich.edu
